{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930021501/0265.xml":{"full_text":"(Ehf Inramsvtllc HeralO\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter in the Poe to flIce\nBrownsville. Texas.\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSabscrlption Rates\u2014Dally and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Year ..$9.00\nElz Months .$4.50\nThree Months. $2.25\nOne Month.75\n\nMEMBER OP THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively entitled to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to it or\nnot otherwise credited in this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nHarlingen Office, Reese-Wil-Mond Hotel. Phone 1020.\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas. Texas, 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo., 306 Coca Cola Building.\nChicago, 111.. Association Building.\nNew York, 350 Madison Avenue.\n8t. Louis. 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles, Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg.,\n646 S. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Cal., 318 Kohl Building.\nWhy Should the Legislature\nWorry?\nWhy should the Texas legislature worry The\nVery staid and dignified Dallas News editorially ask\ned the question and, with becoming modesty, the\neditor of the News answered his own questionnaire:\n\u201cIt is not of course, necessary for Texas to do any\nthing about its prison system. It is true that it is\ncrowding men within its prison walls, housing them\nunder unsanitary conditions and giving them no ade\nquate employment of their time. BUT THESE MEN\nARE CRIMINALS. It is true tliat the antiquated\npenal system of Texas is 50 years behind enlightened\nconsideration of constructive administration and re\nhabilitation. But, should the legislature worry itself\nover incarecrated men and women when it is busy\ncm important matters, such as the distinction be\ntween tweedle-dum and tweedle-de?\"\nSpeaking of the cost of the prison system, the very\nstaid and dignified News editorialized as follows: \u201cTo\nbe sure, the prison farms have not paid during the\nwhole period of their use. And imprisoned men can\nand do escape from the friendly penal shelter pro\nvided those assigned to them. This fact may alarm\nthe immediate neighborhood, but it need not alarm\nthe legislature.\"\nIn conclusion the editor of the North Texas daily\nreminded Ills readers that \"test holes and known views\nki the legislature lend no encouragement to the be\nlief that anything will be done for the reorganiza\ntion of tire prison system during the special session.\"\nla the last analysis, the editorial pot-shotter of North\nTexas finds consolation in this reflection. \"Texas, the\nlegislature, all of us. can go our ways and attend\nto our separate businesses. Reorganization of the\nprison system concerns only helpless men. men con\nvicted of crime, those who have no right to question\nwhat the slate may do for them or permit others\nto do for them. Their debt, of course, is to society.\nSociety owes them no debt that it can be forced to\nrecognize\nThe Herald reminds its North Texas contemporary\nthat a majority of the senators voted to close the\nrat holes where the taxpayers' money made its escape\nto parts unknown for a quarter of a century and that\nperhaps before adjournment a majority of the rep\nresentatives may decide it the part of wisdom to vote\nfor a measure that will be acceptable to the thinking\ntaxpayers of the state.\nTo continue to \"keep the rat holes open\" may pro\nvoke the wrath of the people at the primary polls\nin July and again in November when the finishing\nCouches are put to the final balloting by the men and\nwomen of Texas who are not hangovers from the ox\ncart period of civilization, and cumbersome as well as\nantiquated prison methods of those bygone times.\nThere Is Money in Oil\nProof of the pudding is in its eating There is money\n\u00abn oil. A statement by the president of the Humble\nOil company, speaking of profits for 1929. shows ap\nproximately $32,000,000. \"or roundly, nine and two\ntenths per cent on a fair valuation of the properiie:\nof the company.'\u2019 This is better than in 1928 when\nthe Humble statement showed a profit of six and\nnine-tenths per cent.\nIt Is the contention of the Independents that they\nare the producers of 70 per cent of the crude petro\nleum from wells In the United States. Just now the\nindependents arc asking for a tariff of a dollar per\nbarrel on foreign crude as well as a tariff on its\nby-products which are shipped from the Mexican\npetroleum regions and three South American re\npublics.\nWill they get the tariff? Not while Big Business\nrules the roost on the banks of the Potomac river.\nPolitics is a fascinating game. Free hides come\nin from South America. There isn't a tannery in\nthe hide producing section of the Southwest. Crude\npetroleum comes in from South America and Mexi\nco. It is on the free list. Box and his co-workers\nare for shutting out all labor from Mexico, Central\nand Pan American republics.\nTheir products are landed on these shores free of\nduty but the toilers who get out the foreign products\nare to be barred by law from making their way\nthrough American ports of entry. Tariff making is\na funny game to say the least.\n\n-V\nThe Once Over\nBy H. L PHILLIPS\nLINES FROM A SKEPTICAL BALL FAN.\n(Copyright. 1930. by The Associated Newspapers.)\nWhen Hoover quits as ruler of the nation,\nWhen Lindbergh gives up traveling by air.\nWhen Whiteman says he's through with syncopation\nAnd Paderewski shaves off all his hair;\nWhen Brisbane scraps his pen and ceases writing,\nWhen Borah quits discussion and debate,\nWhen Edison opposes electric lighting\nAnd Arthur Shires says he isn't great.\nWhen Jimmy Walker makes a public statement\nAnnouncing he will always b? on time.\nWhen Mellon no more talks of tax abetement\nAnd Rockefeller gives no one a dime;\nWhen Rudy Vallee quits his microphoning.\nWhen A1 Smith kisses Heflin on the cheek.\nWhen Libby Holman cuts out all that moaning\nAnd Ringling fires ev\u2019ry clown and freak;\nWhen Byrd sits down and gives up all exploring.\nWhen Stimson thinks big navies are the thing,\nWhen Mussolini cuts out all that roaring\nAnd Rosa Ponselle spurns a chance to sing;\nWhen Dempsey enters partnership with Tunney,\nWhen Boston rules no books are really bad.\nWhen Mr. Erookhart ceases being funny\nAnd Joison says. \"I'm only just a fad\";\nWhen Greta Garbo gives up heavy necking\nAnd Gilbert leaves the talking pictures flat.\nWhen woodpeckers abandon woodland pecking\nAnd Scarf ace Whoziss throws away his gat;\nWhen all the Whitneys sell their racing stables\nAnd give the sport of kings the open gate.\nWhen Mr. Mackey gives away his cables\nAnd Peggy Joyce no longer seeks a mate;\nWhen Zlegfeld ceases all his glorifying\nAnd Georgie White decides to riui a bank.\nWhen Mr. Byrd abandons polar flying\nAnd Bishop Cannon says. \"I\u2019m just a crank\u201d;\nWhen Tammany quits playing Rlng-a-Roscy.\nWhen Coolidgc says. \"I\u2019m through keeping still\u201d,\nWhen all dry aeents cease their being nosey\nAnd there is not a pickle known as \u201cDill\";\nWhen Mr. Dawes decides a pipe is horrid.\nWhen Boston waives all credit for the bean.\nWhen Mae West won't play in a show that's torrid\nAnd Mary Pickford quits the movie screen;\nWhen Scars and Roebuck part to take up painting.\nWhen both the Brothers Smith go get a shave.\nWhen Tommy Loughran gives up all that feinting\nAnd Lauder saws. \"A cent I'll never save\u201d;\nWhen Grover Whalen cuts out all those tall hats.\nWhen Morgan cuts quite loose from all the banks\nAnd Spaulding ceases making balls and ball bats\u2014\nTHATS WHEN I THINK BABE RUTH WILL\nQUIT THE YANKS!\nNOTHING LIKE FRANKNESS\nGIRL rants cleanin* University 3878. Ask for\nGeraldine \"\u2014New York Times.\n_\nPresident Hoover Is to tto fishinft off Florida on\nthe houseboat Sauntercr. Here's hoping the Coast\nGuard doesn't fire on him.\n\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN.Stanley\n/TELL her to\nTALK LOUDER\nS--J (SRANOMAVW\nAIMTCSE-THN\np^jjYY uiNE NEWS-JTHE BUZZARD RAMU.Y\nMISSED THIS WEEKS ISSUE OP THE\nClarion\"' but m\u00abs ppsyor oave\nTHEM ALL THE NEWS PIT TO P/^/NT\nt fA II\nThe Good Physician\n\n\u201cBrass Tacks\u201d on the Sunday School Lesson\na Che 6ol6ett Cext\nI-.-- i\n\u201cHimself took our infirmities, end bare our sicknesses.\"\u2014Mat*\ntbew 8:17.\nBY UK. ALi l.N t. BLLl.\nHaving laid clown th\u00bb basic prin\nciples of his kingdom in the Sermon\non the Mount, the King proceeds to\ndemonstrate his right to lay claim\nto kingship by giving illustrations oi\nhis royal power in every conceivable\nrealm. In the realm of disease he I\nproves his kingship by his cure oi\nleprosy, palsy and fever; In the real\nof the deep by stilling the tempest\non Galilee; in the realm of dement\nby casting spirits out of the demon\niacs of Gadarea; in the realm oi\ndeity by absolving the paralytic oi\nhis sins; in the realm of death by\nraising to life, the daughter of\nJairus: and in the realm of dark\nness by opening the eyes of two\nblind men. What credentials of roy\nalty these arc. that the Lord Jesus j\neffers to prove his royalty in every\nrealm\u2014disease, deep, demons, deity,\ndeath and darkness.\nThe Golden Key cf Faith\nThe key that opened the royal\ntreasures to the Kink s bcneficiar.es\nwas the golden key of faith. \u2018Lord,\nif thou wilt, thou canst make n.?\nclean;\u201d \u201cSpeak the word only and\nmy servant shall be healed;\" \"Lord,\nsave us; we perish;\u201d \u201cJesus seeing\ntheir iaith said, eon, be of good\ncheer; thy sins be forgiven thee;\u201d\n\u201cMy daughter is even now dead;\nbut come and lay thy hand upon\nher. and she shall live;\u201d \u201cIf I may\nbut touch his garment, I shall be\nwhole;\u201d \"Believe ye that I am able\nto do this? The blind men said unto\nhim. Yea* Lord.\u201d So in every case,\nfaith opened the treasures of the\nriches of the King as he responded.\n*'I will; be thou clean;\u201d \"I have not\nfound so great faith, no. not in Is\nrael;\u201d \"As thou hast believed, so be\nbe it unto thee;\" \"Thy faith hath\nmade thee whole;\" \"According to\nyour Iaith. be it unto you.\"\nThe Invisible Illustrated\nOur Lord's chief object in all Ins\nmiracle was to bring a spiritual.!\nrather than a physical blessing. The\nmiracle was necessary to project the\ninvisible upon the screen of the vis\nible. This is best shown in today\u2019s I\nlesson on the hcalng of the para\nlytic. whose four friends, with un\ndaunted faith, tore an opening in\nthe roof and lowered their helpless,\nbut believing friend into the pres\nence of Jesu3.\nLike a good physician, Jesus dis\nungmsnca ir.sianuy oe.ween uwi\nv. h.ch was basic ar.d that which was\nmerely eymptomic. A patient with\na sore k:iec often has his basic ail\nment net in the knee, but in his\nteeth. So here, a man is brought to\nthe Good Physician to be treated\nfor palsy, and \"Jesus seeing their\nfaith said unto the sick of the parsy\nSou. be of good cheer; thy sins be\nforgiven thee.\" The Physician's\ncritics sitting by were entirely logical\nin their reasoning when they came\nto their conclusion. \"Th.s man blas\nphemeth\u2019\u2019 for \"Who can forgive sins\nbut God a'.one?\" The fault in tlieir\nlogic was that their major premise\nwas wmg, m that it described Jesus\nas mcreiy this man\", whereas, he\nwas God os well as man, as he pro\nceeded to demonstrate to them:\n\"Wherefore think ye evil in your\nhearts? For whether is eas.er to\nsay, Arise, and walk? But that ye\nmay know that the Son cl Man hath\npower on earth to forgive sins. (Then\nmith he to the sick of the palsy*\nArise, take up thy bed. and go unto\nshine house.\" Our need of Him is\nrealized onlv as we appreciate that\nwe ere spirituaily sick, far \"They\nthat are whole have no need of a\nphysician, but they that are sick.\"\n(The International Uniform Les\nsen for Feb. 16 is Matt.. 9:1-13. the\nsubject being. \"Jesus Healing and\nHelping\" and tho Gsice:i T:xt. Matt\n8:17, \"Himself took cur infirmities,\nand bare our diseases.\"*\nBENEFIT PAGEANT\nEverybody should see the Mer\nchants Pageant. Trades Display and\nStyle Show at the Junior Hr/1\nSchool auditorium Monday and\n'Tuesday night next week. Feb. 17th\nend 13th. Over one hundred people\nwill take part in the exercises.. .all\nhome talent...The young ladies of\nBrownsville will represent the bus\niness f irms... on the sta tre.. Fmc\ndrills and parades, catchy songs,\ntalks and acts and stunts... Some\nthing good, something different...\nYou will like it. Come bring the\nwhole family.. Tickets only 15c and\n35c. Benefit building fund of the\nnew Christian church. Large crowd?\narc expected. Your patronage wil\nbe appreciated Tell your friends\nabout It...Don\u2019t forget the dates\nand place. Adv\nGRACE LUTHERAN MISSION\nGrace Lutheran Mission of the\nUnited Lutheran Church in Amerl-1\nca will hold their services in the\nEpiscopal Parish house Sunday af\nternoon at 3 o'clock. All welcome.\nN. Scheffer, Pastor.\nAMERICAN SPIRITUALISTIC\nHarlingen\nThe Rev. E. V. Sloots will lecture\non the power or God at the Sun\nday evening service. He will be as\nsisted by Mrs. Aug. Barber. Service\nbegins 7:30 p. m.\nAt the Odd Fellows hall, N. P.\nand West Monroe.\nCHRISTIAN UNITY\n509 Elizabeth St.\n9:45-10:45 a. m. Sunday Services.\n8 p. m.\u2014Wednesday, song and\nprayer service, testimonials.\n9:30 a. m Tuesday, workers'\nmeeting.\n3-4 p. m.\u2014 Friday, study classes\nconducted by Mrs. Thomss.\nMrs. Thomas in office each\nmorning. 9 to 11:30.\nLUTHERAN CHURCH\nRev. H. L. Wiedranders, Pastor\nServices every Sunday In the\nJunior High school auditorium at\n9 a. m. Sunday School at 10 a. m.\nVOLUNTEERS OF AMERICA\n820 Elizabeth St\n7:30 p. m.. preaching service.\nPrayer meeting weekly at 7:30\nI P. m.\nSACRED HEART CHURCH\nWinter Regulation\n7:00 a. m. Mass and holy com\nmunion.\n9:15 a. m. Sunday school and Bi\nble class.\n10:00 a. m. Kijh mass and ser\nmon.\n7:30 Vespers. S\u00bbrmon. benediction\nof the blessed Sacrament.\nFi-n\ntar Society at 3:30 p. m\nFirst Friday: Devotions to the\nSacred Heart, 7.00 a. m. and 7.00\nn m\nFirst Sunday: Meeting of the\nChildren of Mary. 3:30 p. m.\nSecond Sunday: Meeting of the\nHoly name Society 7:30 p. m.\nWeek Days: Divine sendee every\nmorning at seven o'clock.\nJean B Frigon, O. M I LL. D.,\nPastor.\n\nCHURCH OF THE ADVENT\n(Episcopal)\nChurch school and Bible class,\nHoly communion, 7:30 a. m.\n9:30 a. m.\nMorning prayer and sermon, 11\na. m.\nEvening service, 7:30 p. m.\nR. O. MACKINTOSH.\nCENTRAL CHRISTIAN CHURCH\n(Twelfth and Jefferson Streets)\n(Masonic Temple)\n9:45 a. m. Bible School, Sher\nwood Bishop, superintendent.\n11:00 a. m. Morning worship and\nCommunion service.\n11:20 a m. Sermon\u2014Arbitration\nGeo. F. Dennis.\n6:30 p. m Christian Endeavor\nProgram.\nThere will be no evening worship\nat the temple. We unite with the\nother churches in a Union service\nat the Methodist Church.\nA hearty welcome is extended to\nall visitors to attend these services.\nThere are classes in the Bible School\nto suit all ages.\nGeo. F. Dennis. Secretary\nMEXICAN METHODIST\niTavlor and 13th Sts.)\n9:45\u2014Graded and departmental\nized Sunday school. J. de la Paz\nGarcia. superintendent.\n7:30 n. m.. Preaching Sendee, voc\nare all welcome to the house ol\nOf od\nTuesday, 7:30 p. m Prayer meet\nD J de la Garza, pastor\nF\u2019RST BAPTIST CHURCH\n9 45 Graded and Department\nized Sunday School. Ewing D. Clark\nSuo't.\n10:55 Morning Worshm:\nPrelude-Triumphal March-Heln\ntze.\nnosology Invocation Gloria\nPatria.\nHymn No. 1.\nSeripturc Reading\nHvmn No. 210.\nOffertory\u2014Reverie\u2014Flagler.\nAnthem\u2014Out of The Depths\nRocers\nSermon by the aPstor Theme\nAPPLIQUE DRESS TRIMMING\nr|lHiS smart applique trimming\nX requires no special skill but\nIt gives the dressmaker fin\nish to a new dress that is so de\nsirable. The pattern for the ap\nplique pieces Is given here in\nactual else. Cut this out, lay on\na piece of cardboard, trace and\nthen cut from the cardboard.\nFrom this cardboard you will be\nable to cut the material to be\nused for the appliques.\nTaffeta la a good material to\nuse for the appliques since this Is\nclosely woven and Arm and docs\nnot need to be turned In around\nthe edges. Taffeta may be used\neffectively on crepe de chine, or\ngandie or other light cotton ma\nterials for light afternoon or even\ning dresses. Velvet may be used\nfor the appliques on woolen ma\nterials or silks, metal cloth may\nbe used for evening dresses or\nheavy linen on dresses of cotton\nor lighter weight linen.\nCut the pieces from the pattern\nand then arrange in group* a*j\n'shown In the sketch. Baste the\npieces on the material in this\ngroup formation.\nIt you are working on aheer\nmaterial It Is a good plan to\nmake a tracing of the group of\nappliques on a piece of paper.\nThen attach this to the hack of\nthe material to which they are\napplied, baste the pieces to the\nmaterial and the paper and when\nhasted, carefully tear away the\npaper. If you use velvet or taf\nfeta appliques they do not need\nto be turned under around the\nedges.\nI se fine silk and a fine needle\nand blind stitch around the\nedges. If you like you may fasten\nthe pieces down by an even row\nof French knots around the edge.\nIf you use material that frays\neasily you should turn the ap\npliques under around the edges\nBaste under the material and\npress thoroughly on the wrong\n*ide before laying on the m\u00ab.\nteriaJ.\nThe Tempter. His Origin, Titles.\nMission, Method and Defeat.\nHymn No. 120.\nPostlude\u2014Allegro\u2014King.\nThe general public together with\nstrangers and visitors in the city\nare invited to attend all the ser\nvices of this church. There will\nbe no evening worship, the services\nbeing dispensed with to attend the\ncommunity service at the First\nMethodist church.\n\u25a0in\nCHRISTIAN SCIENCE SOCIETY\n(Corner Elizabeth and West Second\nStreets)\nChristian Science Society o f\nBrownsville. Texes, a branch of The\nMother Church, First Church of\nChrist Scientist in Boston. Massa\nchusetts.\nSunday School at 9:45 a. m.\nSunday morning services at 11:00.\nSubject: \u2018Soul'\u2019\nA Wednesday evening testimoni\nal meeting at 8 00 o'clock.\nReading Room in the church\nbuilding open Tuesday and Fridays\nfrom 2:00 to 5:00 p. m.\nFIRST METHODIST CHURCH\n9:30 Sunday School. Mens Bible\nClass meets at Queen theatre. W.\nW. Underwood supt.\n10:30 a. m.\u2014Worship service\nPrelude \u2018'Romance\u201d (Zitterbartv, j\nhymn No. 334, \"Apostles Creed.\u201d j\nprayer. Hymn No. 108. scripture\nreading from Psalms \"Gloria Patrl.\u201d j\noffertorv song. \u201cIn the Night\u201d: An-\nthem. \"The Lord Is My Light.\u201d,\nchoir: sermon. \"Faith Is the Vic- I\ntorvPostlude. \"ConzoRe.\" Har- j\nrisi\n6:30 p. m.\u2014Epworth Leagues\nmeet\n7:30 p. m.\u2014Special Union Ser\nvice. Prelude, \u201cNocturne. Chopin)\nHvmn. Prayer Offertory \u201cGavotte''\nThomas'. Duette Mr and Mrs\nTrimble. Dr. George W. Morrow will\ndeliver an address on \"Law En\nforcement\". Dr. Morrow is a noted\nsneaker and will give vou some\nthing worthwhile. Do not lull to\nhear him.\n3 00 p. m. Mondav\u2014Woman' Mi'\nsior.arv Society will meet at the\nchurch for a social meeMng.\n7:30 n. m Wednesday\u2014Mission\nStudy clas\u00ab _\nJ. E LOVETT. Pastor\npm ST PRE*BVTFR*AN CHURCH\n(Flizabeth Sfree* and Palm Bird\nMotring Prelude. \u201cOffertoire in E\nFl\u00abt Faulkes.\nOffertory. \"Ave Mnr(e CaI*.\nPostlude \u201cFestival Postlude In B\nFlat\u201d. Liebig.\nAnthf\u00bbm. A Wandering Ship. Ira\nB Wilson. _\nMominiz sermon bv Mr. o.on\nAvres nrlncinal of Olmtto 'choc\nNo evening services on arconnt or\nunion meeting at Methodis* church.\nSenior League will present lan\ntern slides on medical missions lr.\nChina at 8 45. Visitors invited\nJunior League Tuesday at 4\no'clock\nAuxiliary study meeting. Monday\n3:30. Mrs Bascom Cox in charge\nof program on Home Mission?.\n\nLabor Organization f\nPlans Incorporation\n(Special to The Herald)\nSAN BENITO. Feb. 13.\u2014Articles\nol incorporation for the Rio Grande\nValley, Inc., have been prepared,\nand have been signed by most of the\nnine directors.\nThey wil be forwarded to Austin\nMonday, upon the return to the\nValley of J. E. Bell, one of the di\nrectors, who is now in San An\ntonio on the freight differential\ncase.\nOther preparations for carrying\nout the work of this organization,\nwhich is to protect the Valley's Mex\nican labor, are being made.\nThe membership stock ecrtificates\nhave been pfinted.\nA meeting of the directors will be\nheld soon after the incorporation,\naccording to Mr. Lomax, to take up\nthe question of selecting a man\nager.\nA finance '^mmtttee also is to\nbe named, to lu^ndle the raiding of\nfunds for the ^organization\n[ATTENTION! f\nWe have added a\nRental Library' to our\nt store! Come in and look I\n9 it over. All of the best\nj sellers of all publishers. X\nI Keep abreast of the J\nP most popular new books\nby renting them at I\nt small cost!\nI HARGROVE\u2019S j\nI Stationery Book Store I\nL Phone 348\nBrownsville, Texas\nFEED GRAIN\nAND\nHAY\nMcLELLAND FEED CO..\nPhone 765 568 N. Commerc\nHarlingen\nEat At\nAnthony\u2019s Waffle\nI Shop\n517 12 St Phone 983\nA. TAMM\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen, Texas\n1911 1930\nSkelton Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nMerchants Bank Building Brownsville\nDependable Phone 353 Prompt\nBROWNSVILLE TITLE COMPANY\nBROWNSVILLE. TEXAS\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nWe cover all land* In Camer\u00abn County\nCARNEIRO, CHUMNEY COMPANY\nCertified Public Accountants\nIncome Tax Servlet\nBROWNSVILLE SAN ANTONIO CORPUS CHRISTI\nState National Bank Smith-Young Tower Nixon Building\n-PROSPERITY\nProsperity for Brownsville and\nthe Valley is a tangible, able-to\nbc-seen condition. Citrus groves\nare beginning to bloom vege\ntables are commanding good\nprices generally the interna\ntional airport and the bright\nprospects for a deep water port\u2014\nall are encouraging a splendid\nbusiness outlook for Erownsville\nand the Valley.\nLet us, as your bank, help\nyou with any problems you\nmay' wish to discuss with us.\nFirst National Bank\nEstablithed in 1S91\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\nTITLE INSURANCE\nWhen yon borrow money on real estate, many loan companies re\nquire the title to be insured. Ibe best test of whether a title\ninsurable, is to have it insured. Require a title insurance policy\nwhen yon buy.\nVALLEY ABSTRACT COMPANY\nPrompt Title Service\nBrownsville Edinburg\nOpposite Court House E- Harriman Bird.\nPhone 1181 Phone 93","height":"35984","width":"27176"}}
